{"title_page": "Rheindahlen", "text_new": "{{About|the German town|the former British base named after it|JHQ Rheindahlen}}\n{{Infobox Ortsteil einer Gemeinde in Deutschland\n| Art                    = Stadtteil\n| City                   = M\u00f6nchengladbach\n| Wappen                         = Wappen Rheindahlen.png\n|coordinates        = {{coord|51|09|01|N|06|21|42|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| Bundesland                     = North Rhine-Westphalia\n| H\u00f6he                           = 65-80\n| Fl\u00e4che                         = 3.237\n| Einwohner                      = 27363\n| Stand                          = 2008-12-31\n| PLZ                            = 41179\n| Vorwahl                        = 02161\n| Lageplan                       = MG-Rheindahlen-Mitte.svg\n| Lageplanbeschreibung           = Location of Rheindahlen within M\u00f6nchengladbach\n}}\n'''Rheindahlen''' (called ''Dalen'' from the [[Early Middle Ages]] to the [[Early Modern Period]] around 1700, and ''Dahlen'' until 1878) is a town in the western and largest borough of the city of [[M\u00f6nchengladbach]] in the German state of [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]. Since the reorganisation of Monchengladbach's boroughs (''Stadtbezirke'') on 22 October 2009 Rheindahlen has been part of M\u00f6nchengladbach West. From the granting of [[Nideggen]] town rights in 1354 until the incorporation of the mayoralty of Rheindahlen into M.-Gladbach on 30 June 1921, the place was an independent town.\n\nIn 1878, the town was renamed from ''Dahlen'' to ''Rheindahlen'' in the [[Prussia]]n [[D\u00fcsseldorf (region)|Province of D\u00fcsseldorf]] by order of Emperor [[William I (German Emperor)|William I]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archive.nrw.de/Kommunalarchive/KommunalarchiveM-P/M/Moenchengladbach/InformationenUndService/AllgemeineInformationen/Verwaltungszugehoerigkeit.html|title=Verwaltungszugeh\u00f6rigkeit|publisher=Landesarchiv Nordrhein-Westfalen|accessdate=2011-01-01}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Its renaming was primarily for postal reasons in order to avoid confusing the Dahlen in the [[Rhine Province]] with the municipality of [[Dahlen (Saxony)|Dahlen in Saxony]] within the North German Postal Zone. Its old name linguistically meant ''Delle'' or \"hollow\", which refers to the location of the village in a depression.\n\n== Geography ==\n=== Location and surrounding area ===\nRheindahlen is located in M\u00f6nchengladbach West, the largest urban district in the city of M\u00f6nchengladbach. It lies to the south-west of the main urban area and borders on the municipality of [[Schwalmtal (Lower Rhine)|Schwalmtal]] to the west and the county of [[Kreis Heinsberg|Heinsberg]] to the southwest. Its neighbouring communities within the borough of M\u00f6nchengladbach are Hardt to the north, Rheydt to the east and Wickrath to the south. The centre of Rheindahlen is about 7.5 kilometres southwest of the city centre of M\u00f6nchengladbach.\n\n=== Landscape and geology ===\nAround Rheindahlen, the landscape is dominated by the western foothills of [[J\u00fclich-Z\u00fclpich B\u00f6rde]]. It is situated on the southern edge of the [[Lower Rhine Plain]] on the [[Schwalm (Meuse)|Schwalm]]-[[Nette (Niers)|Nette]] Plateau which, in the western part of the borough is characterised by wetlands and woods. To the south is the source region of the [[Niers]]. The Rheindahlen landscape lies on the southern edge of the M\u00f6nchengladbach Loam Plain and rises towards the south. Its lowest point measures {{H\u00f6he|65|DE-NN}}, its highest point is {{H\u00f6he|80|DE-NN}}. The village itself is 70\u2013{{H\u00f6he|73|DE-NN}}.\n\nGeologically, the area belongs to the [[Lower Rhine Bay]] on whose western edge it lies.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Michael Walter|editor-surname1= Zukunft Rheindahlen e.&nbsp;V.|title=Blickpunkte: Rheindahlener Geschichte|publisher=Eigenverlag|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|page=9|contribution=Seit 65 Millionen Jahren \u2013 Entstehung unserer Landschaft|date=2004|language=German\n}}</ref> Its topmost soil layer consists mainly of [[loess]] which is highly suitable for agriculture and which was deposited during the [[Last glacial period|last ice age]] in a layer up to 10 metres thick on the gravels and sands of the Rhine. Beneath this upper layer are gravels, sands, clays, and brown coal strata of the [[Tertiary]]. The [[brown coal]] seams of the Lower Rhine Bay are very thick in places and are mined in large [[open-cast pit]]s (in the area of Rheindalen in the [[Garzweiler Mine]]); The brown coal seam of ''Morken'' has, for example, a [[thickness (geology)|thickness]] of around 150 metres. In permeable, beds such as gravel and sands, [[groundwater]] is present on several superimposed levels. These levels are separated by relatively impermeable layers of silt and clay.\n\nThe groundwater is pumped out by wells and drainage measures around the opencast mine of Garzweiler. This extraction of the groundwater results in widespread mining damage as a result of subsidence. In some cases, the drainage even causes movements on the otherwise inactive geological faults which subdivide the Lower Rhine Bay. The \"Rheindahlen Fault\", which runs an east-west direction, has moved as a result of the drainage measures. It runs from the direction of the former British base of [[JHQ Rheindahlen]] to the district [[Rheydt]] and is responsible for mining damage due to lowering of the groundwater and the resulting sedimentary movements along the Rheydt and G\u00fcnhoven [[fault block]]s on the territory of Monchengladbach.\n\n=== Climate ===\nThe [[climate]] of Rheindahlen is influenced in particular by the Atlantic [[Gulf Stream]] and its location within the transition between the maritime and continental climatic zones. Precipitation occurs in all seasons and the prevailing wind comes from the south-west. Annual rainfall is around 730 millimetres, with July being the most precipitous and September being the least precipitous month. Summers are usually warm and winters, due to maritime climate, mild. In July, the mean temperature is 20&nbsp;\u00b0C, in January it is 0.5&nbsp;\u00b0C. The duration of the cold period with minimum temperatures below 0&nbsp;\u00b0C is on average less than 60 days, the number of summer days with temperatures above 25&nbsp;\u00b0C is 30 days, with an additional eight \"tropical\" days with daytime temperatures of more than 30&nbsp;\u00b0C and night temperatures above 20&nbsp;\u00b0C, and a total of 20 days can be expected with thunderstorms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nvv-ag.de/new_service/index.htm|title=NiederrheinWasser GmbH \u2013 MDO \u2013 Meteorologische Messdaten|publisher=NiederrheinWasser GmbH|accessdate=2010-10-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819101059/http://www.nvv-ag.de/new_service/index.htm|archivedate=2010-08-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Subdivisions ===\nThe former borough of ''Rheindahlen'' (since 2009 [[M\u00f6nchengladbach West]]) consists of the nine districts of Wickrath-Mitte, Wickrath-West, Wickrathberg, Wanlo, [[Hehn (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Hehn]], [[Holt (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Holt]], [[JHQ Rheindahlen|Hauptquartier]], [[Rheindahlen-Land]] and Rheindahlen-Mitte.\n\nWhilst ''Rheindahlen-Mitte'' is limited to the town intself and the surrounding streets and residential areas that grew up after the [[Second World War]], ''Rheindahlen-Land'' covers 36 so-called ''[[Honnschaft|Honschaften]]'' around the centre of Rheindahlen, as follows:\n\n{| class=\"nowraplinks\" style=\"border: 2px #D3D3D3 solid; border-collapse: collapse;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color: #E0E0E0; padding: 2px 0 2px 5px; text-align: left;\"| '''Honschaften, [[Rheindahlen-Land]]'''<br /><span style=\"font-size:0.9em;\">M\u00f6nchengladbach, [[M\u00f6nchengladbach West|Stadtbezirk West]]</span>\n|-\n| rowspan=15 style=\"text-align: center; padding: 5px;\"| [[File:MG-Rheindahlen-Land.svg|300px]]\n<span style=\"font-size:0.9em;\">Overview map of ''Rheindahlen-Land''<br />in the Monchengladbach borough</span>\n|-\n| [[Bau (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Bau]]\n| [[Gerkerathwinkel (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Gerkerathwinkel]]\n| [[Merreter (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Merreter]]\n|-\n| [[Baum (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Baum]]\n| [[Griesbarth (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Griesbarth]]\n| [[Peel (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Peel]]\n|-\n| [[Broich (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Broich]]\n| [[Grotherath (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Grotherath]]\n| [[Saas (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Saas]]\n|-\n| [[Dorthausen]]\n| [[G\u00fcnhoven (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|G\u00fcnhoven]]\n| [[Schriefers (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Schriefers]]\n|-\n| [[Eickelnberg (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Eickelnberg]]\n| [[Herdt (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Herdt]]\n| [[Schriefersm\u00fchle (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Schriefersm\u00fchle]]\n|-\n| [[Gatzweiler (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Gatzweiler]]\n| [[Hilderath (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Hilderath]]\n| [[Sittard (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Sittard]]\n|-\n| [[Genhausen (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Genhausen]]\n| [[Knoor (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Knoor]]\n| [[Sittardheide (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Sittardheide]]\n|-\n| [[Genhodder (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Genhodder]]\n| [[Koch (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Koch]]\n| [[Viehstra\u00dfe (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Viehstra\u00dfe]]\n|-\n| [[Genholland (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Genholland]]\n| [[Kothausen (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Kothausen]]\n| [[Voosen (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Voosen]]\n|-\n| [[Genh\u00fclsen (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Genh\u00fclsen]]\n| [[Mennrath (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Mennrath]]\n| [[Wolfsittard (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Wolfsittard]]\n|-\n| [[Gerkerath (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Gerkerath]]\n| [[Mennrathheide (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Mennrathheide]]\n| [[Woof (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Woof]]\n|-\n| [[Gerkerathm\u00fchle (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Gerkerathm\u00fchle]]\n| [[Mennrathschmidt (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Mennrathschmidt]]\n| [[Wyenh\u00fctte (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Wyenh\u00fctte]]\n|-\n|<br /><br />\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" style=\" background-color: #E0E0E0; text-align: center; padding: 5px;\"| [http://www.moenchengladbach.de/index.php?id=stadtbezirke&L=0 Information about Monchengladbach's boroughs and districts]\n|}\n\nIn 1833 the following ''Honschaften'' were part of the mayoralty of Rheindahlen:<ref name=\"rheinprovinz107\">{{citation|title=Die Rheinprovinz der preussischen Monarchie, oder Beschreibung der systematischen Eintheilung in Regierungsbezirke, Kreise, B\u00fcrgermeistereien und Honnschaften, so wie der St\u00e4dte, Flecken, D\u00f6rfer, einzelner Etablissements, mit Angabe der Einwohnerzahl, Gewerbe, Merkw\u00fcrdigkeiten, Anstalten u. s. w.: Ein historisch=geographisch=statistisches Handbuch zum Gebrauch aller St\u00e4nde. Aus den neuesten Quellen gesch\u00f6pft und zusammengestellt von mehreren Gelehrten|volume=I. Band|location=D\u00fcsseldorf|at=p.&nbsp;107|date=1833|language=German|url=[http://digital.ub.uni-duesseldorf.de/ihd/content/zoom/2250360 Seite im Digitalisat der Heinrich-Heine-Universit\u00e4t D\u00fcsseldorf]|access-date=2012-10-04\n}}</ref><ref name=\"rheinprovinz108\">{{citation|title=Die Rheinprovinz der preussischen Monarchie, oder Beschreibung der systematischen Eintheilung in Regierungsbezirke, Kreise, B\u00fcrgermeistereien und Honnschaften, so wie der St\u00e4dte, Flecken, D\u00f6rfer, einzelner Etablissements, mit Angabe der Einwohnerzahl, Gewerbe, Merkw\u00fcrdigkeiten, Anstalten u. s. w.: Ein historisch=geographisch=statistisches Handbuch zum Gebrauch aller St\u00e4nde. Aus den neuesten Quellen gesch\u00f6pft und zusammengestellt von mehreren Gelehrten|volume=I. Band|location=D\u00fcsseldorf|page=108|date=1833|language=German|url=http://digital.ub.uni-duesseldorf.de/ihd/content/zoom/2250361 |work=digital.ub.uni-duesseldorf.de |access-date=2012-10-04}}</ref>\n* The [[hamlet (place)|hamlet]]s of: Bau, Baum, Bockert (not [[Bockert]] which is part of [[Viersen]]), Dorthausen, Eickelnberg, Genhausen, Genhodder, Griesbart, Grotherath, G\u00fcnhoverh\u00fctte, Knoor, Kothausen, Mennratherheid, Saas, Schmidt, Schrievers, Viehstra\u00df, Winkel\n* The villages of: Broich, Genh\u00fclsen, Gerkerath, G\u00fcnhoven, Koch, Mennrath. Wolfsittard\n* The ''Honschaften'' of: Aufm Feldchen, Gatzweiler, Genholland, Herdt, Hilderath, Merreter, Sittard, Sittardheid, Voosen, Woof, Wyenh\u00fctt\n* The farms of: Gennenh\u00f6fchen, Martinenh\u00f6fchen, S\u00fcdderatherhof\n* The mills of: Gerkeratherm\u00fchle (windmill), [[Knippertzm\u00fchle]] (water mill), Schriefersm\u00fchle (windmill), [[Vollm\u00fchle (Gatzweiler)|Vollm\u00fchle]] (water mill)\n* The isolated houses of: Peel, An der Stappen\n\nThe postal code of Rheindahlen is 41179. Until the introduction of five-digit post codes it was 4050 M\u00f6nchengladbach 5.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:C Sgrothen Atlas 1557.jpg|thumb|1557 map of the Lower Rhine region, between the Rhine, Erft and Rur with the village of Dalen in the north]]\n[[File:Erkelant.jpg|thumb|upright=1|Dalen in the manuscript atlas by [[Christian Sgrothen]], before 1573]]\n[[File:Dalen1644.png|thumb|Fanciful portrayal of the town at the time of the Hessian plundering on 9 May 1644. The clearly Dutch engraving is taken from the left hand side of the [[:File:The siege of Dalen on july 22, 1568 (Frans Hogenberg).jpg|depiction]] by [[Frans Hogenberg]]. The copperplate engraver can have had no knowledge of the town, as can be seen from the incorrect number of towers and the town wall with arrow slits and battlement gables.]]\n[[File:Rheindahlen Tranchot 1801-1828.png|thumb|Dahlen and surroundings on the 1806/07 [[Jean Joseph Tranchot|Tranchot]] map]]\n\n=== Pre- and early history ===\nThe remains of settlements from the [[Old Stone Age|Old]] and [[New Stone Age]]s, between 220,000 and 120,000 BC, have been found in Rheindahlen. They could be [[fossil]]s of ''[[Homo erectus]]'' ''([[Homo heidelbergensis]])'' and [[Neandertal Man]].<ref>{{citation|author1=Heinz G\u00fcnter Horn |editor1=Dirk L. Krausse |editor2=J\u00fcrgen Kunow |editor3=Egon Schallmayer |editor4=Regina Smolnik |editor5=C. Sebastian Sommer|periodical=Arch\u00e4ologie in Deutschland|title=Bodendenkmalpflege in NRW: Geschichte vor der Haust\u00fcr|issue=2|publisher=Konrad Theiss Verlag|location=Stuttgart|pages=20\u201324|date=2005|language=German|author1-link=Heinz G\u00fcnter Horn }}</ref> Rheindahlen is also an extremely rich site for fossil remains that have survived in the soil which is mainly clay. In archaeological circles the site has been nationally well known since 1908.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Michael Walter|editor-surname1= Zukunft Rheindahlen e.&nbsp;V.|title=Blickpunkte: Rheindahlener Geschichte|publisher=Eigenverlag|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|page=13|contribution=600.000 Jahre alt \u2013 Rheindahlen ist einer der bedeutendsten Fundorte in Europa|date=2004|language=German\n}}</ref> In the recent past, in the southern part of the borough, near an old brickworks, archaeological excavations took place that have contributely decisively to the understanding of the hunting and settlement areas of Neandertal man.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nespos.org/display/PublicNesposSpace/Rheindahlen|title=Public NESPOS Space \u2013 Rheindahlen|publisher=NESPOS Society e.&nbsp;V.|language=English|accessdate=2010-10-19}}</ref> A thirteen-fold enlarged bronze replica of the hand hammer found in 1994 has been on display in the centre of Rheindahlen since 2003; it recalls the early history of the village.<ref>{{citation|editor-surname1= Zukunft Rheindahlen e.V|title=Rheindahlen \u2013 650 Jahre: Festschrift zur 650-Jahr-Feier|publisher=Bern Sch\u00fcren|location=Rheindahlen|page=11|date=2004|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\nFrom the 3rd century A.D. a Roman settlement is known to have existed in the [[Hardt Forest]] to the north. This was discovered in 1954 during the construction of the [[JHQ Rheindahlen|NATO Headquarters]] northwest of Rheindahlen.<ref>{{citation|author1=Wolfgang L\u00f6hr|editor1= Stadtarchiv M\u00f6nchengladbach|title=Rheindahlen: Ein Bildband|publisher=B. K\u00fchlen|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|page=14|isbn=3-87448-070-4|date=1971|language=German\n}}</ref> Clues as to Roman settlements were found ''inter alia'' at Genholland, Genh\u00fclsen, Griesbarth, Hilderath, Merreter and Peel, including a 2nd-century, [[metre]]-high [[Matres and Matrones|matrona]] stone discovered in 1961<ref>{{citation|editor-surname1= Otto von Bylandt-Stiftung zur F\u00f6rderung des St\u00e4dtischen Museums Schlo\u00df Rheydt|title=Rheydter Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Geschichte, Kunst und Heimatkunde|volume=14|publisher=B. K\u00fchlen Verlag|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|pages=67&nbsp;ff|date=1982|language=German\n}}</ref> and probably the remains of a road.<ref name=\"rsa\">{{citation|author1=Wolfgang L\u00f6hr|editor1= Georg Droege |editor2=Klaus Fehn |editor3=Klaus Fink |title=Rheinischer St\u00e4dteatlas: Rheindahlen|publisher=Rheinland-Verlag|location=K\u00f6ln|isbn=3-7927-0305-X|date=1976|language=German|title-link= Rheinischer St\u00e4dteatlas }}</ref> In 2010, excavations uncovered cellar vaults and buildings which were dated to the period from the 10th to the 13th centuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rp-online.de/niederrheinsued/moenchengladbach/nachrichten/Hinab-ins-Mittelalter_aid_849665.html|title=Hinab ins Mittelalter|publisher=RP Online|author=Wiljo Krechting|date=2010-04-27|accessdate=2010-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100509005043/http://www.rp-online.de/niederrheinsued/moenchengladbach/nachrichten/Hinab-ins-Mittelalter_aid_849665.html#|archive-date=2010-05-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> In addition there were early mediaeval [[motte castle]]s in Mennrath, Sittard and Schriefershof.<ref name=\"rsa\" /><ref>{{citation|surname1=Wolfgang L\u00f6hr|editor1= Stadtarchiv M\u00f6nchengladbach|title=Rheindahlen: Ein Bildband|publisher=B. K\u00fchlen|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|page=16|isbn=3-87448-070-4|date=1971|language=German}}</ref>\n\n=== Etymology ===\nThe original name of Rheindahlen was ''Dale'', which appeared probably in the 9th or 10th centuries when terrain names for [[human settlement|settlements]] was common. The word ''Dale'' is derived in this case from ''Dal'', which means \"valley\" or \"hollow\" and is similar to the English word \"dale\".<ref>{{citation|surname1=Toni Mennen|title=Genhodder \u2013 550 Jahre|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|pages=12 f|contribution=Kurzfassung der Rheindahlener (Genhodder) Geschichte|date=2002|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\nWhilst the name ''Dalen'' was used until around 1500<ref>{{citation|surname1=Toni Mennen|title=Genhodder \u2013 550 Jahre|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|page=13|contribution=Kurzfassung der Rheindahlener (Genhodder) Geschichte|date=2002|language=German\n}}</ref> and at the latest until 1700, it changed in the early 18th century to ''Dahlen''. Due to the number of places with the name ''Dahl'', ''Dalheim'', ''Dalem'' and ''Dalhem'' it became increasingly difficult for postal services, which began around 1870, to distinguish between the individual settlements. Because of the location of Dahlen in the Rhine Province of Prussia, it was decided to rename the town ''Rheindahlen''. This was authorised by an act by the Prussian king, William I dated 24 December 1877. The act was published in the Prussian Ministerial Record on 15 February 1878.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Robert Jeuckens|editor-surname1= Bisch\u00f6fliches Di\u00f6zesanarchiv Aachen|title=Geschichte von Stadt und Pfarre Rheindahlen|volume=20|location=Aachen|page=45|date=1954|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 20th century the municipal authorities of the town of Rheindahlen advised that Rheindahlen should be incorporated into the town of Gladbach. The then Lord Mayor of Gladbach, [[Hermann Piecq]] planned the incorporation of Neuwerk, Gladbach-Land and Rheindahlen. This happened on 18 July 1921 and thus Rheindahlen lost its independence and from then on was called M.Gladbach-Rheindahlen. After the Second World War the name became ''Rheindahlen''.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Robert Jeuckens|editor-surname1= Bisch\u00f6fliches Di\u00f6zesanarchiv Aachen|title=Geschichte von Stadt und Pfarre Rheindahlen|volume=20|location=Aachen|pages=45 f|date=1954|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\n=== Manorialism ===\nDalen was first mentioned in 861 as a village (Lat.: ''villa'') in the [[M\u00fchlgau]] (Lat.: ''pago molense''), which belonged to the [[Bishopric of Liege]].<ref>{{citation|surname1=Heinrich Gr\u00f6teken|editor-surname1= Stadt Rheindahlen|title=Geschichte der Stadt und des Amtes Dahlen|publisher=A. Reuter, M.Gladbach Rheindahlen|page=7|date=1925|language=German\n}}</ref> Six years later it is recorded as ''Dalon'', a clearance settlement probably on a royal estate in the time of the [[Carolingians]].<ref>{{citation|author1=Wolfgang L\u00f6hr |editor1=Georg Droege |editor2=Klaus Fehn |editor3=Klaus Fink |title=Rheinischer St\u00e4dteatlas: Rheindahlen|publisher=Rheinland-Verlag|location=K\u00f6ln|page=1|isbn=3-7927-0305-X|date=1976|language=German\n}}</ref> [[Etymologically]] ''Dalen'' derives from ''Delle'' or \"small valley\". In the archives of [[Pr\u00fcm Abbey]] is the copy of a document according to which King [[Lothair II (Lorraine)|Lothair II]] exchanged goods and estates on 20 January 867 with ''Otbert'', a [[vassal]] of Count II from the [[Eifelgau]].<ref>{{citation|surname1=Norbert Becker|editor1= Wolfgang L\u00f6hr |title=Loca Desiderata, M\u00f6nchengladbacher Stadtgeschichte|volume=1|publisher=Rheinland-Verlag- und Betriebsgesellschaft des Landschaftsverbandes Rheinland|location=Abtei Brauweiler, Pulheim|page=419|isbn=3-7927-1375-6|date=1994|language=German\n}}</ref> Amongst other things, the king transferred to him in the [[Moselgau]] in the March of ''wanolon''<ref>{{citation|surname1=W. Jungandreas|title=Historisches Lexikon der Siedlungs- und Flurnamen des Mosellandes|location=Trier|page=1093|date=1962|language=German\n}}</ref> an ''[[Amt (country subdivision)|Amt]]'' as a [[fief]] of Sigar: {{quote|''in pago moslense in commarca wanolon benificium Sigari\u2026''}} Due to this translation error, ''Dalon'' was incorrectly held to be the present day Rheindahlen. However, it is more likely that [[Spangdahlem]] near [[Pr\u00fcm]] in the [[Eifel]] was meant.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Toni Mennen |author2=Michael Walter|editor1= B\u00fcrgerverein Rheindahlen |editor2=Heimatverein Beeck |title=Die mittelalterliche Burg Gripekoven und die Herrschaft Dalen: Der gescheiterte Versuch, eine niederrheinische Herrschaft zu errichten, Teil 1: Die Wickrath-Hochstaden-Are und das Kirchspiel Dalen|volume=1|location=Rheindahlen|page=53|date=1990|language=German\n}}</ref> A clue to that are the surviving records of the Cologne abbey of ''Cunibert'', which describe [[tithe]] rights of the abbey in [[Bernkastel-Kues|Wehlen]] on the [[Moselle]]. Another indication that ''Dalon'' was not the later Dahlen is reinforced by the fact that neither in the present day Rheindahlen itself nor the surrounding villages have any traces from the time of the [[Carolingians]] or the [[Merovingians]] been found.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Toni Mennen |author2=Michael Walter|editor-surname1= B\u00fcrgerverein Rheindahlen  |editor2=Heimatverein Beeck |title=Die mittelalterliche Burg Gripekoven und die Herrschaft Dalen: Der gescheiterte Versuch, eine niederrheinische Herrschaft zu errichten, Teil 1: Die Wickrath-Hochstaden-Are und das Kirchspiel Dalen|volume=1|location=Rheindahlen|pages=54\u201355|date=1990|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* {{DNB-Portal|4284658-4|TYP=Literature about}}\n* {{DNB-Portal|4284619-5|TYP=Literature about|NAME=the district of Rheindalen}}\n* {{dmoz|World/Deutsch/Regional/Europa/Deutschland/Nordrhein-Westfalen/St\u00e4dte_und_Gemeinden/M/M\u00f6nchengladbach/Stadtteile/|accessdate=2010-12-28}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.zukunft-rheindahlen.de/index.html|title=Zukunft Rheindahlen. Wir denken an morgen.|publisher=Zukunft Rheindahlen e.&nbsp;V.|date=2010-12-16|accessdate=2010-12-28}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.geschichtsfreunde-rheindahlen.de/|title=Geschichtsfreunde RheinDahlen|publisher=Sigrid Bruckmann|accessdate=2014-01-28}}\n\n[[Category:Former municipalities in North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:M\u00f6nchengladbach]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the German town|the former British base named after it|JHQ Rheindahlen}}\n{{Infobox Ortsteil einer Gemeinde in Deutschland\n| Art                    = Stadtteil\n| City                   = M\u00f6nchengladbach\n| Alternativanzeige-Gemeindename =\n| Wappen                         = Wappen Rheindahlen.png\n| Ortswappen-Beschreibung        = Coat of arms of the former town of Rheindahlen\n|coordinates        = {{coord|51|09|01|N|06|21|42|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| Bundesland                     = North Rhine-Westphalia\n| H\u00f6he                           = 70 <!-- Quelle: Geodatenzentrum -->\n| H\u00f6he-von                       = 65\n| H\u00f6he-bis                       = 80\n| Fl\u00e4che                         = 3.237\n| Einwohner                      = 27363\n| Stand                          = 2008-12-31\n| Eingemeindungsdatum            = 1921-06-30\n| PLZ                            = 41179\n| Vorwahl                        = 02161\n| Lageplan                       = MG-Rheindahlen-Mitte.svg\n| Lageplanbeschreibung           = Location of Rheindahlen within M\u00f6nchengladbach West\n}}\n'''Rheindahlen''' (called ''Dalen'' from the [[Early Middle Ages]] to the [[Early Modern Period]] around 1700, and ''Dahlen'' until 1878) is a town in the western and largest borough of the city of [[M\u00f6nchengladbach]] in the German state of [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]. Since the reorganisation of Monchengladbach's boroughs (''Stadtbezirke'') on 22 October 2009 Rheindahlen has been part of M\u00f6nchengladbach West. From the granting of [[Nideggen]] town rights in 1354 until the incorporation of the mayoralty of Rheindahlen into M.-Gladbach on 30 June 1921, the place was an independent town.\n\nIn 1878, the town was renamed from ''Dahlen'' to ''Rheindahlen'' in the [[Prussia]]n [[D\u00fcsseldorf (region)|Province of D\u00fcsseldorf]] by order of Emperor [[William I (German Emperor)|William I]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archive.nrw.de/Kommunalarchive/KommunalarchiveM-P/M/Moenchengladbach/InformationenUndService/AllgemeineInformationen/Verwaltungszugehoerigkeit.html|title=Verwaltungszugeh\u00f6rigkeit|publisher=Landesarchiv Nordrhein-Westfalen|accessdate=2011-01-01}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Its renaming was primarily for postal reasons in order to avoid confusing the Dahlen in the [[Rhine Province]] with the municipality of [[Dahlen (Saxony)|Dahlen in Saxony]] within the North German Postal Zone. Its old name linguistically meant ''Delle'' or \"hollow\", which refers to the location of the village in a depression.\n\n== Geography ==\n=== Location and surrounding area ===\nRheindahlen is located in M\u00f6nchengladbach West, the largest urban district in the city of M\u00f6nchengladbach. It lies to the south-west of the main urban area and borders on the municipality of [[Schwalmtal (Lower Rhine)|Schwalmtal]] to the west and the county of [[Kreis Heinsberg|Heinsberg]] to the southwest. Its neighbouring communities within the borough of M\u00f6nchengladbach are Hardt to the north, Rheydt to the east and Wickrath to the south. The centre of Rheindahlen is about 7.5 kilometres southwest of the city centre of M\u00f6nchengladbach.\n\n=== Landscape and geology ===\nAround Rheindahlen, the landscape is dominated by the western foothills of [[J\u00fclich-Z\u00fclpich B\u00f6rde]]. It is situated on the southern edge of the [[Lower Rhine Plain]] on the [[Schwalm (Meuse)|Schwalm]]-[[Nette (Niers)|Nette]] Plateau which, in the western part of the borough is characterised by wetlands and woods. To the south is the source region of the [[Niers]]. The Rheindahlen landscape lies on the southern edge of the M\u00f6nchengladbach Loam Plain and rises towards the south. Its lowest point measures {{H\u00f6he|65|DE-NN}}, its highest point is {{H\u00f6he|80|DE-NN}}. The village itself is 70\u2013{{H\u00f6he|73|DE-NN}}.\n\nGeologically, the area belongs to the [[Lower Rhine Bay]] on whose western edge it lies.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Michael Walter|editor-surname1= Zukunft Rheindahlen e.&nbsp;V.|title=Blickpunkte: Rheindahlener Geschichte|publisher=Eigenverlag|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|page=9|contribution=Seit 65 Millionen Jahren \u2013 Entstehung unserer Landschaft|date=2004|language=German\n}}</ref> Its topmost soil layer consists mainly of [[loess]] which is highly suitable for agriculture and which was deposited during the [[Last glacial period|last ice age]] in a layer up to 10 metres thick on the gravels and sands of the Rhine. Beneath this upper layer are gravels, sands, clays, and brown coal strata of the [[Tertiary]]. The [[brown coal]] seams of the Lower Rhine Bay are very thick in places and are mined in large [[open-cast pit]]s (in the area of Rheindalen in the [[Garzweiler Mine]]); The brown coal seam of ''Morken'' has, for example, a [[thickness (geology)|thickness]] of around 150 metres. In permeable, beds such as gravel and sands, [[groundwater]] is present on several superimposed levels. These levels are separated by relatively impermeable layers of silt and clay.\n\nThe groundwater is pumped out by wells and drainage measures around the opencast mine of Garzweiler. This extraction of the groundwater results in widespread mining damage as a result of subsidence. In some cases, the drainage even causes movements on the otherwise inactive geological faults which subdivide the Lower Rhine Bay. The \"Rheindahlen Fault\", which runs an east-west direction, has moved as a result of the drainage measures. It runs from the direction of the former British base of [[JHQ Rheindahlen]] to the district [[Rheydt]] and is responsible for mining damage due to lowering of the groundwater and the resulting sedimentary movements along the Rheydt and G\u00fcnhoven [[fault block]]s on the territory of Monchengladbach.\n\n=== Climate ===\nThe [[climate]] of Rheindahlen is influenced in particular by the Atlantic [[Gulf Stream]] and its location within the transition between the maritime and continental climatic zones. Precipitation occurs in all seasons and the prevailing wind comes from the south-west. Annual rainfall is around 730 millimetres, with July being the most precipitous and September being the least precipitous month. Summers are usually warm and winters, due to maritime climate, mild. In July, the mean temperature is 20&nbsp;\u00b0C, in January it is 0.5&nbsp;\u00b0C. The duration of the cold period with minimum temperatures below 0&nbsp;\u00b0C is on average less than 60 days, the number of summer days with temperatures above 25&nbsp;\u00b0C is 30 days, with an additional eight \"tropical\" days with daytime temperatures of more than 30&nbsp;\u00b0C and night temperatures above 20&nbsp;\u00b0C, and a total of 20 days can be expected with thunderstorms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nvv-ag.de/new_service/index.htm|title=NiederrheinWasser GmbH \u2013 MDO \u2013 Meteorologische Messdaten|publisher=NiederrheinWasser GmbH|accessdate=2010-10-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819101059/http://www.nvv-ag.de/new_service/index.htm|archivedate=2010-08-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Subdivisions ===\nThe former borough of ''Rheindahlen'' (since 2009 [[M\u00f6nchengladbach West]]) consists of the nine districts of Wickrath-Mitte, Wickrath-West, Wickrathberg, Wanlo, [[Hehn (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Hehn]], [[Holt (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Holt]], [[JHQ Rheindahlen|Hauptquartier]], [[Rheindahlen-Land]] and Rheindahlen-Mitte.\n\nWhilst ''Rheindahlen-Mitte'' is limited to the town intself and the surrounding streets and residential areas that grew up after the [[Second World War]], ''Rheindahlen-Land'' covers 36 so-called ''[[Honnschaft|Honschaften]]'' around the centre of Rheindahlen, as follows:\n\n{| class=\"nowraplinks\" style=\"border: 2px #D3D3D3 solid; border-collapse: collapse;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color: #E0E0E0; padding: 2px 0 2px 5px; text-align: left;\"| '''Honschaften, [[Rheindahlen-Land]]'''<br /><span style=\"font-size:0.9em;\">M\u00f6nchengladbach, [[M\u00f6nchengladbach West|Stadtbezirk West]]</span>\n|-\n| rowspan=15 style=\"text-align: center; padding: 5px;\"| [[File:MG-Rheindahlen-Land.svg|300px]]\n<span style=\"font-size:0.9em;\">Overview map of ''Rheindahlen-Land''<br />in the Monchengladbach borough</span>\n|-\n| [[Bau (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Bau]]\n| [[Gerkerathwinkel (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Gerkerathwinkel]]\n| [[Merreter (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Merreter]]\n|-\n| [[Baum (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Baum]]\n| [[Griesbarth (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Griesbarth]]\n| [[Peel (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Peel]]\n|-\n| [[Broich (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Broich]]\n| [[Grotherath (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Grotherath]]\n| [[Saas (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Saas]]\n|-\n| [[Dorthausen]]\n| [[G\u00fcnhoven (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|G\u00fcnhoven]]\n| [[Schriefers (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Schriefers]]\n|-\n| [[Eickelnberg (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Eickelnberg]]\n| [[Herdt (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Herdt]]\n| [[Schriefersm\u00fchle (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Schriefersm\u00fchle]]\n|-\n| [[Gatzweiler (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Gatzweiler]]\n| [[Hilderath (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Hilderath]]\n| [[Sittard (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Sittard]]\n|-\n| [[Genhausen (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Genhausen]]\n| [[Knoor (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Knoor]]\n| [[Sittardheide (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Sittardheide]]\n|-\n| [[Genhodder (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Genhodder]]\n| [[Koch (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Koch]]\n| [[Viehstra\u00dfe (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Viehstra\u00dfe]]\n|-\n| [[Genholland (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Genholland]]\n| [[Kothausen (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Kothausen]]\n| [[Voosen (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Voosen]]\n|-\n| [[Genh\u00fclsen (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Genh\u00fclsen]]\n| [[Mennrath (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Mennrath]]\n| [[Wolfsittard (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Wolfsittard]]\n|-\n| [[Gerkerath (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Gerkerath]]\n| [[Mennrathheide (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Mennrathheide]]\n| [[Woof (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Woof]]\n|-\n| [[Gerkerathm\u00fchle (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Gerkerathm\u00fchle]]\n| [[Mennrathschmidt (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Mennrathschmidt]]\n| [[Wyenh\u00fctte (M\u00f6nchengladbach)|Wyenh\u00fctte]]\n|-\n|<br /><br />\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" style=\" background-color: #E0E0E0; text-align: center; padding: 5px;\"| [http://www.moenchengladbach.de/index.php?id=stadtbezirke&L=0 Information about Monchengladbach's boroughs and districts]\n|}\n\nIn 1833 the following ''Honschaften'' were part of the mayoralty of Rheindahlen:<ref name=\"rheinprovinz107\">{{citation|title=Die Rheinprovinz der preussischen Monarchie, oder Beschreibung der systematischen Eintheilung in Regierungsbezirke, Kreise, B\u00fcrgermeistereien und Honnschaften, so wie der St\u00e4dte, Flecken, D\u00f6rfer, einzelner Etablissements, mit Angabe der Einwohnerzahl, Gewerbe, Merkw\u00fcrdigkeiten, Anstalten u. s. w.: Ein historisch=geographisch=statistisches Handbuch zum Gebrauch aller St\u00e4nde. Aus den neuesten Quellen gesch\u00f6pft und zusammengestellt von mehreren Gelehrten|volume=I. Band|location=D\u00fcsseldorf|at=p.&nbsp;107|date=1833|language=German|url=[http://digital.ub.uni-duesseldorf.de/ihd/content/zoom/2250360 Seite im Digitalisat der Heinrich-Heine-Universit\u00e4t D\u00fcsseldorf]|access-date=2012-10-04\n}}</ref><ref name=\"rheinprovinz108\">{{citation|title=Die Rheinprovinz der preussischen Monarchie, oder Beschreibung der systematischen Eintheilung in Regierungsbezirke, Kreise, B\u00fcrgermeistereien und Honnschaften, so wie der St\u00e4dte, Flecken, D\u00f6rfer, einzelner Etablissements, mit Angabe der Einwohnerzahl, Gewerbe, Merkw\u00fcrdigkeiten, Anstalten u. s. w.: Ein historisch=geographisch=statistisches Handbuch zum Gebrauch aller St\u00e4nde. Aus den neuesten Quellen gesch\u00f6pft und zusammengestellt von mehreren Gelehrten|volume=I. Band|location=D\u00fcsseldorf|page=108|date=1833|language=German|url=http://digital.ub.uni-duesseldorf.de/ihd/content/zoom/2250361 |work=digital.ub.uni-duesseldorf.de |access-date=2012-10-04}}</ref>\n* The [[hamlet (place)|hamlet]]s of: Bau, Baum, Bockert (not [[Bockert]] which is part of [[Viersen]]), Dorthausen, Eickelnberg, Genhausen, Genhodder, Griesbart, Grotherath, G\u00fcnhoverh\u00fctte, Knoor, Kothausen, Mennratherheid, Saas, Schmidt, Schrievers, Viehstra\u00df, Winkel\n* The villages of: Broich, Genh\u00fclsen, Gerkerath, G\u00fcnhoven, Koch, Mennrath. Wolfsittard\n* The ''Honschaften'' of: Aufm Feldchen, Gatzweiler, Genholland, Herdt, Hilderath, Merreter, Sittard, Sittardheid, Voosen, Woof, Wyenh\u00fctt\n* The farms of: Gennenh\u00f6fchen, Martinenh\u00f6fchen, S\u00fcdderatherhof\n* The mills of: Gerkeratherm\u00fchle (windmill), [[Knippertzm\u00fchle]] (water mill), Schriefersm\u00fchle (windmill), [[Vollm\u00fchle (Gatzweiler)|Vollm\u00fchle]] (water mill)\n* The isolated houses of: Peel, An der Stappen\n\nThe postal code of Rheindahlen is 41179. Until the introduction of five-digit post codes it was 4050 M\u00f6nchengladbach 5.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:C Sgrothen Atlas 1557.jpg|thumb|1557 map of the Lower Rhine region, between the Rhine, Erft and Rur with the village of Dalen in the north]]\n[[File:Erkelant.jpg|thumb|upright=1|Dalen in the manuscript atlas by [[Christian Sgrothen]], before 1573]]\n[[File:Dalen1644.png|thumb|Fanciful portrayal of the town at the time of the Hessian plundering on 9 May 1644. The clearly Dutch engraving is taken from the left hand side of the [[:File:The siege of Dalen on july 22, 1568 (Frans Hogenberg).jpg|depiction]] by [[Frans Hogenberg]]. The copperplate engraver can have had no knowledge of the town, as can be seen from the incorrect number of towers and the town wall with arrow slits and battlement gables.]]\n[[File:Rheindahlen Tranchot 1801-1828.png|thumb|Dahlen and surroundings on the 1806/07 [[Jean Joseph Tranchot|Tranchot]] map]]\n\n=== Pre- and early history ===\nThe remains of settlements from the [[Old Stone Age|Old]] and [[New Stone Age]]s, between 220,000 and 120,000 BC, have been found in Rheindahlen. They could be [[fossil]]s of ''[[Homo erectus]]'' ''([[Homo heidelbergensis]])'' and [[Neandertal Man]].<ref>{{citation|author1=Heinz G\u00fcnter Horn |editor1=Dirk L. Krausse |editor2=J\u00fcrgen Kunow |editor3=Egon Schallmayer |editor4=Regina Smolnik |editor5=C. Sebastian Sommer|periodical=Arch\u00e4ologie in Deutschland|title=Bodendenkmalpflege in NRW: Geschichte vor der Haust\u00fcr|issue=2|publisher=Konrad Theiss Verlag|location=Stuttgart|pages=20\u201324|date=2005|language=German|author1-link=Heinz G\u00fcnter Horn }}</ref> Rheindahlen is also an extremely rich site for fossil remains that have survived in the soil which is mainly clay. In archaeological circles the site has been nationally well known since 1908.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Michael Walter|editor-surname1= Zukunft Rheindahlen e.&nbsp;V.|title=Blickpunkte: Rheindahlener Geschichte|publisher=Eigenverlag|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|page=13|contribution=600.000 Jahre alt \u2013 Rheindahlen ist einer der bedeutendsten Fundorte in Europa|date=2004|language=German\n}}</ref> In the recent past, in the southern part of the borough, near an old brickworks, archaeological excavations took place that have contributely decisively to the understanding of the hunting and settlement areas of Neandertal man.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nespos.org/display/PublicNesposSpace/Rheindahlen|title=Public NESPOS Space \u2013 Rheindahlen|publisher=NESPOS Society e.&nbsp;V.|language=English|accessdate=2010-10-19}}</ref> A thirteen-fold enlarged bronze replica of the hand hammer found in 1994 has been on display in the centre of Rheindahlen since 2003; it recalls the early history of the village.<ref>{{citation|editor-surname1= Zukunft Rheindahlen e.V|title=Rheindahlen \u2013 650 Jahre: Festschrift zur 650-Jahr-Feier|publisher=Bern Sch\u00fcren|location=Rheindahlen|page=11|date=2004|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\nFrom the 3rd century A.D. a Roman settlement is known to have existed in the [[Hardt Forest]] to the north. This was discovered in 1954 during the construction of the [[JHQ Rheindahlen|NATO Headquarters]] northwest of Rheindahlen.<ref>{{citation|author1=Wolfgang L\u00f6hr|editor1= Stadtarchiv M\u00f6nchengladbach|title=Rheindahlen: Ein Bildband|publisher=B. K\u00fchlen|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|page=14|isbn=3-87448-070-4|date=1971|language=German\n}}</ref> Clues as to Roman settlements were found ''inter alia'' at Genholland, Genh\u00fclsen, Griesbarth, Hilderath, Merreter and Peel, including a 2nd-century, [[metre]]-high [[Matres and Matrones|matrona]] stone discovered in 1961<ref>{{citation|editor-surname1= Otto von Bylandt-Stiftung zur F\u00f6rderung des St\u00e4dtischen Museums Schlo\u00df Rheydt|title=Rheydter Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Geschichte, Kunst und Heimatkunde|volume=14|publisher=B. K\u00fchlen Verlag|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|pages=67&nbsp;ff|date=1982|language=German\n}}</ref> and probably the remains of a road.<ref name=\"rsa\">{{citation|author1=Wolfgang L\u00f6hr|editor1= Georg Droege |editor2=Klaus Fehn |editor3=Klaus Fink |title=Rheinischer St\u00e4dteatlas: Rheindahlen|publisher=Rheinland-Verlag|location=K\u00f6ln|isbn=3-7927-0305-X|date=1976|language=German|title-link= Rheinischer St\u00e4dteatlas }}</ref> In 2010, excavations uncovered cellar vaults and buildings which were dated to the period from the 10th to the 13th centuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rp-online.de/niederrheinsued/moenchengladbach/nachrichten/Hinab-ins-Mittelalter_aid_849665.html|title=Hinab ins Mittelalter|publisher=RP Online|author=Wiljo Krechting|date=2010-04-27|accessdate=2010-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100509005043/http://www.rp-online.de/niederrheinsued/moenchengladbach/nachrichten/Hinab-ins-Mittelalter_aid_849665.html#|archive-date=2010-05-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> In addition there were early mediaeval [[motte castle]]s in Mennrath, Sittard and Schriefershof.<ref name=\"rsa\" /><ref>{{citation|surname1=Wolfgang L\u00f6hr|editor1= Stadtarchiv M\u00f6nchengladbach|title=Rheindahlen: Ein Bildband|publisher=B. K\u00fchlen|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|page=16|isbn=3-87448-070-4|date=1971|language=German}}</ref>\n\n=== Etymology ===\nThe original name of Rheindahlen was ''Dale'', which appeared probably in the 9th or 10th centuries when terrain names for [[human settlement|settlements]] was common. The word ''Dale'' is derived in this case from ''Dal'', which means \"valley\" or \"hollow\" and is similar to the English word \"dale\".<ref>{{citation|surname1=Toni Mennen|title=Genhodder \u2013 550 Jahre|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|pages=12 f|contribution=Kurzfassung der Rheindahlener (Genhodder) Geschichte|date=2002|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\nWhilst the name ''Dalen'' was used until around 1500<ref>{{citation|surname1=Toni Mennen|title=Genhodder \u2013 550 Jahre|location=M\u00f6nchengladbach|page=13|contribution=Kurzfassung der Rheindahlener (Genhodder) Geschichte|date=2002|language=German\n}}</ref> and at the latest until 1700, it changed in the early 18th century to ''Dahlen''. Due to the number of places with the name ''Dahl'', ''Dalheim'', ''Dalem'' and ''Dalhem'' it became increasingly difficult for postal services, which began around 1870, to distinguish between the individual settlements. Because of the location of Dahlen in the Rhine Province of Prussia, it was decided to rename the town ''Rheindahlen''. This was authorised by an act by the Prussian king, William I dated 24 December 1877. The act was published in the Prussian Ministerial Record on 15 February 1878.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Robert Jeuckens|editor-surname1= Bisch\u00f6fliches Di\u00f6zesanarchiv Aachen|title=Geschichte von Stadt und Pfarre Rheindahlen|volume=20|location=Aachen|page=45|date=1954|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 20th century the municipal authorities of the town of Rheindahlen advised that Rheindahlen should be incorporated into the town of Gladbach. The then Lord Mayor of Gladbach, [[Hermann Piecq]] planned the incorporation of Neuwerk, Gladbach-Land and Rheindahlen. This happened on 18 July 1921 and thus Rheindahlen lost its independence and from then on was called M.Gladbach-Rheindahlen. After the Second World War the name became ''Rheindahlen''.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Robert Jeuckens|editor-surname1= Bisch\u00f6fliches Di\u00f6zesanarchiv Aachen|title=Geschichte von Stadt und Pfarre Rheindahlen|volume=20|location=Aachen|pages=45 f|date=1954|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\n=== Manorialism ===\nDalen was first mentioned in 861 as a village (Lat.: ''villa'') in the [[M\u00fchlgau]] (Lat.: ''pago molense''), which belonged to the [[Bishopric of Liege]].<ref>{{citation|surname1=Heinrich Gr\u00f6teken|editor-surname1= Stadt Rheindahlen|title=Geschichte der Stadt und des Amtes Dahlen|publisher=A. Reuter, M.Gladbach Rheindahlen|page=7|date=1925|language=German\n}}</ref> Six years later it is recorded as ''Dalon'', a clearance settlement probably on a royal estate in the time of the [[Carolingians]].<ref>{{citation|author1=Wolfgang L\u00f6hr |editor1=Georg Droege |editor2=Klaus Fehn |editor3=Klaus Fink |title=Rheinischer St\u00e4dteatlas: Rheindahlen|publisher=Rheinland-Verlag|location=K\u00f6ln|page=1|isbn=3-7927-0305-X|date=1976|language=German\n}}</ref> [[Etymologically]] ''Dalen'' derives from ''Delle'' or \"small valley\". In the archives of [[Pr\u00fcm Abbey]] is the copy of a document according to which King [[Lothair II (Lorraine)|Lothair II]] exchanged goods and estates on 20 January 867 with ''Otbert'', a [[vassal]] of Count II from the [[Eifelgau]].<ref>{{citation|surname1=Norbert Becker|editor1= Wolfgang L\u00f6hr |title=Loca Desiderata, M\u00f6nchengladbacher Stadtgeschichte|volume=1|publisher=Rheinland-Verlag- und Betriebsgesellschaft des Landschaftsverbandes Rheinland|location=Abtei Brauweiler, Pulheim|page=419|isbn=3-7927-1375-6|date=1994|language=German\n}}</ref> Amongst other things, the king transferred to him in the [[Moselgau]] in the March of ''wanolon''<ref>{{citation|surname1=W. Jungandreas|title=Historisches Lexikon der Siedlungs- und Flurnamen des Mosellandes|location=Trier|page=1093|date=1962|language=German\n}}</ref> an ''[[Amt (country subdivision)|Amt]]'' as a [[fief]] of Sigar: {{quote|''in pago moslense in commarca wanolon benificium Sigari\u2026''}} Due to this translation error, ''Dalon'' was incorrectly held to be the present day Rheindahlen. However, it is more likely that [[Spangdahlem]] near [[Pr\u00fcm]] in the [[Eifel]] was meant.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Toni Mennen |author2=Michael Walter|editor1= B\u00fcrgerverein Rheindahlen |editor2=Heimatverein Beeck |title=Die mittelalterliche Burg Gripekoven und die Herrschaft Dalen: Der gescheiterte Versuch, eine niederrheinische Herrschaft zu errichten, Teil 1: Die Wickrath-Hochstaden-Are und das Kirchspiel Dalen|volume=1|location=Rheindahlen|page=53|date=1990|language=German\n}}</ref> A clue to that are the surviving records of the Cologne abbey of ''Cunibert'', which describe [[tithe]] rights of the abbey in [[Bernkastel-Kues|Wehlen]] on the [[Moselle]]. Another indication that ''Dalon'' was not the later Dahlen is reinforced by the fact that neither in the present day Rheindahlen itself nor the surrounding villages have any traces from the time of the [[Carolingians]] or the [[Merovingians]] been found.<ref>{{citation|surname1=Toni Mennen |author2=Michael Walter|editor-surname1= B\u00fcrgerverein Rheindahlen  |editor2=Heimatverein Beeck |title=Die mittelalterliche Burg Gripekoven und die Herrschaft Dalen: Der gescheiterte Versuch, eine niederrheinische Herrschaft zu errichten, Teil 1: Die Wickrath-Hochstaden-Are und das Kirchspiel Dalen|volume=1|location=Rheindahlen|pages=54\u201355|date=1990|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* {{DNB-Portal|4284658-4|TYP=Literature about}}\n* {{DNB-Portal|4284619-5|TYP=Literature about|NAME=the district of Rheindalen}}\n* {{dmoz|World/Deutsch/Regional/Europa/Deutschland/Nordrhein-Westfalen/St\u00e4dte_und_Gemeinden/M/M\u00f6nchengladbach/Stadtteile/|accessdate=2010-12-28}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.zukunft-rheindahlen.de/index.html|title=Zukunft Rheindahlen. Wir denken an morgen.|publisher=Zukunft Rheindahlen e.&nbsp;V.|date=2010-12-16|accessdate=2010-12-28}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.geschichtsfreunde-rheindahlen.de/|title=Geschichtsfreunde RheinDahlen|publisher=Sigrid Bruckmann|accessdate=2014-01-28}}\n\n[[Category:Former municipalities in North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:M\u00f6nchengladbach]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rheindahlen"}
{"title_page": "List of people buried at sea", "text_new": "[[Image:Burial at sea Feb2004.jpg|300px|thumb|Burial at sea on the [[USS Enterprise (CVN-65)|USS ''Enterprise'']], May 19, 2004]]\nThis is a list of '''people [[Burial at sea|buried at sea]]'''\n* [[Richard B. Anderson]] (1922\u20131944)\n* [[John Carradine]] (1906\u20131988) \n* [[Francis Drake]] (1540\u20131596)\n* [[James Cook|Captain James Cook]] (1728\u20131779)\n* [[George Duff]] (1764\u20131805)\n* [[Frank Watson Dyson]] (1868\u20131939)\n* [[Zheng He]] (1371\u20131433/35)\n* [[Naihekukui]]\n* [[Zachary Hickes]] (d. 1771), first lieutenant aboard [[HMS Endeavour|HMS ''Endeavour'']] on its voyage to Australia<ref>{{cite book |title =The Journals of Captain James Cook on His Voyages of Discovery, vol. I:The Voyage of the Endeavour 1768\u20131771 | first = | last = | coauthors= |editor-last=Beaglehole | editor-first=J.C. | editor-link=John Beaglehole | page = 468| year =1968 | publisher =Cambridge University Press | url = | oclc=223185477}}</ref>\n* [[Arthur Kennedy (governor)|Sir Arthur Kennedy]] (1809\u20131883)\n* [[Christopher Levett]] (1586\u20131630)\n* [[William Lowndes (congressman)|William Lowndes]] (1782-1822), U.S. Congressman from South Carolina\n* [[James Martin (Australian soldier)]] (1901\u20131915)\n* [[Atholl MacGregor]] (1883-1945), [[Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of Hong Kong|Chief Justice of Hong Kong]]\n* [[Edwina Mountbatten, Countess Mountbatten of Burma]] (1901\u20131960)\n* [[Michael Parks]] (1940-2017) \n* [[Ferdinand Schiess|Christian Ferdinand Schiess]] (1856\u20131884) \n* [[Frederic John Walker]] Royal Navy (1896\u20131944)\n* [[Dennis Wilson]] (1944\u20131983)\n* [[Kealiiahonui]] (1800\u20131849)\n* Following the [[death of Osama bin Laden|death of]] [[Osama bin Laden]] (1957\u20132011), he was buried at sea. One U.S. official stated that \"finding a country willing to accept the remains of the world's most wanted terrorist would have been difficult.\"<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/us_bin_laden_burial Yahoo report/ Official: Bin Laden buried at sea]</ref> It was also done to prevent his burial place from becoming a \"terrorist shrine\".<ref>[http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2011/05/osama-bin-laden-body-headed-for-burial-at-sea-officials-say.html/ Osama Bin Laden Body Headed for Burial at Sea, Officials Say] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110503025832/http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2011/05/osama-bin-laden-body-headed-for-burial-at-sea-officials-say.html |date=2011-05-03 }}</ref>\n\n== People whose ashes were scattered at sea ==\n{{multiple image\n|align     = right\n|direction = vertical\n|width     = 200\n|image1    = Janis Joplin 1970.JPG\n|caption1  = [[Janis Joplin]] whose ashes were scattered at the Pacific Ocean\n|image2    = Chyna at Slim-Fast Fashion Show 1.jpg\n|caption2  = [[Chyna]] whose ashes were scattered at the Pacific Ocean\n|image3    = Sridevi.jpg\n|caption3  = [[Sridevi]] whose ashes were scattered at [[Rameswaram]] [[coast]]\n|image4    = JFKJr2.jpg\n|caption4  = [[John F. Kennedy Jr.]] whose ashes were scattered at the Atlantic Ocean\n}}\n\n* [[Bud Abbott]] (1897-1974)\n* [[Hal Ashby]] (1929\u20131988)\n* [[Queen Aishwarya of Nepal]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2xPg44gK3FQ</ref>  (1949\u20132001)\n* [[Jack Albertson]] (1907\u20131981)\n* [[Mabel Albertson]] (1901\u20131982)\n* [[Peter Allen (musician)|Peter Allen]] (1944\u20131992)\n* [[Kirk Alyn]] (1910\u20131999) \n* [[Dev Anand]] (1923\u20132011)\n* [[Edward Andrews]] (1914\u20131985)\n* [[John Anderson (actor)]] (1922\u20131992)\n* [[Roscoe Arbuckle]] (1887\u20131933)\n* [[Neil Armstrong]] (1930-2012)\n* [[Desi Arnaz]] (1917\u20131986)\n* [[Sig Arno]] (1895\u20131975)\n* [[Jean Arthur]] (1900\u20131991)\n* [[Malcolm Atterbury]] (1907\u20131992)\n* [[Edith Atwater]] (1911\u20131986)\n* [[James Avery (actor)|James Avery]] (1945\u20132013) \n* [[Cleo Baldon]] (1927\u20132014)\n* [[Raymond Bailey]] (1904\u20131980)\n* [[Lester Bangs]] (1948\u20131982)\n* [[Lynn Bari]] (1913\u20131989)\n* [[Saul Bass]] (1920\u20131996)\n* [[Hugh Beaumont]] (1909\u20131982)\n* [[Bruce Bennett]] (1906\u20132007)  \n* [[Krishna Prasad Bhattarai]] (1924\u20132011)\n* [[Herbert Biberman]] (1900\u20131971)\n* [[Birendra of Nepal]] (1945\u20132001) <ref>https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2001-jun-03-mn-5969-story.html</ref>\n* [[Joey Bishop]] (1918\u20132007)\n* [[Kirti Nidhi Bista]] (1927\u20132017)\n* [[Bill Bixby]] (1934-1993) (ashes scattered off [[Hana, Hawaii]]) \n* [[Mari Blanchard]] (1923\u20131970)\n* [[Jorge Bolet]] (1914\u20131990)\n* [[Ward Bond]] (1903\u20131960)\n* [[Veda Ann Borg]] (1915\u20131973)\n* [[David Bowie]] (1947\u20132016)\n* [[Lee Bowman]] (1914\u20131979)\n* [[Joseph Boxhall]] (1884 \u20131967) (ashes scattered off [[Atlantic Ocean]])\n* [[Marlon Brando]] (1924-2004)\n* [[Robert Bray]] (1917\u20131983)\n* [[George Brent]] (1904\u20131979)\n* [[Martin E. Brooks]] (1925-2015) \n* [[James Brown (actor)]] (1920\u20131992)\n* [[Phil Brown (actor)]] (1916\u20132006)\n* [[Obadiah Bush]] (1797\u20131851)\n* [[Cliff Burton]] (1962\u20131986)\n* [[Maria Callas]] (1923\u20131977) (Her ashes were originally buried in the P\u00e8re Lachaise Cemetery. After being stolen and later recovered, they were scattered into the Aegean Sea, off the coast of Greece on June 3, 1979) \n* [[Norman Campbell]] (1924\u20132004) (ashes sprinkled off [[Prince Edward Island]]) \n* [[Olive Carey]] (1896\u20131988)\n* [[Allen Carr]] (1934\u20132006)\n* [[Anthony Caruso (actor)|Anthony Caruso]] (1916\u20132003) \n* [[Adriana Caselotti]] (1916\u20131997)\n* [[Jack Cassidy]] (1927\u20131976)\n* [[Joan Caulfield]] (1922\u20131991)\n* [[Dorothy Buffum Chandler]] (1901\u20131997)\n* [[Norman Chandler]] (1899\u20131973)\n* [[Ben Chapman (actor)|Ben Chapman]] (1925\u20132008) (ashes scattered off [[Hawaii]] and at Park Lake (Black Lagoon) at [[Universal Studios]])\n* [[Lonny Chapman]] (1920\u20132007)\n* [[Chyna]] (1969\u20132