{"title_page": "The Double (Seattle Mariners)", "text_new": "[[Image:The Double.jpg|300px|right|thumb|[[Ken Griffey, Jr.]] (center) and the [[1995 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]] celebrate after he scored the winning run in Game 5 of the [[1995 American League Division Series|1995 ALDS]].]]\n'''The Double''' was a [[double (baseball)|double]] hit by the [[1995 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]]' [[Edgar Mart\u00ednez]] in Game 5 of [[Major League Baseball]]'s [[1995 American League Division Series]] on October 8, 1995. Trailing by one run in the bottom half of the 11th inning, with [[Joey Cora]] on third base and [[Ken Griffey, Jr.]] on first, Martinez's [[hit (baseball)|hit]] [[run batted in|drove in]] Cora and Griffey, giving the Mariners a 6\u20135 victory over the [[1995 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] to clinch the series, 3\u20132. The play is held to be the \"biggest hit in franchise history.\"<ref name=\"ESPNHoF\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=1888518&type=story|title=Martinez is beloved by Seattle fans; what about Hall voters?|last=Associated Press|date=2004-09-25|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref>\n\nAmid rumors that the team would be sold and/or relocated, the Mariners\u2014who had had only two winning seasons ([[1991 Seattle Mariners season|1991]] and [[1993 Seattle Mariners season|1993]]) since beginning play in [[1977 Seattle Mariners season|1977]]\u2014mounted a late-season comeback in [[1995 Seattle Mariners season|1995]] to clinch their first postseason appearance in franchise history. They then mounted a series of comebacks in the ALDS, first overcoming a 2-game series deficit to force a deciding Game 5, then tying Game 5 in the 8th inning to force [[extra innings]], and finally a one-run 11th inning deficit that was overcome by the Double.\n\nThe hit is regarded as the defining moment of Martinez's 18-year [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Fame]] career.<ref name=\"ESPNHoF\" /> Mariners broadcaster [[Dave Niehaus]]' call of the play\u2014which is equally memorable to Seattle fans as the play itself\u2014is also regarded as the highlight of his career. The play is also credited with keeping a Major League Baseball team in the city of [[Seattle]], as it helped garner support for a new taxpayer-funded stadium for the Mariners.<ref name=\"Finnigan\">{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2002001226_edgardecision10.html|title=How Martinez arrived at his decision to retire|last=Finnigan|first=Bob|date=2004-08-10|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"PIAndreisen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/baseball/356292_edgar25.html|title=Will Edgar Martinez head to Hall of Fame?|last=Andriesen|first=David|date=2008-03-25|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> That stadium, known today as [[T-Mobile Park]] (it was originally known as Safeco Field through the end of the [[2018 Seattle Mariners season|2018 season]]), opened in [[1999 Seattle Mariners season|1999]], with the Double depicted in a mural as part of the stadium's art collection.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:USS Leahy (CG-16) in front of the Seattle Kingdome Stadium on 6 October 1982 (6371846).jpg|thumb|right|250px|The [[Kingdome]], the Mariners' home stadium from [[1977 Seattle Mariners season|1977]]&ndash;[[1999 Seattle Mariners season|1999]], and site of The Double.]]\n\n===Relocation rumors===\nFor several years the Mariners had been dogged by rumors that the team's ownership group led by [[Jeff Smulyan]] had been considering selling and/or relocating the team to a different city.<ref name=\"NYT\" /><ref name=\"Ms92\">{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19911211&slug=1322349|title=M's Likely Here in '92|last=Judd|first=Ron|author2=Joni Balter |date=1991-12-11|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> This was primarily due to low attendance and revenue,<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/12/sports/baseball-owners-focus-on-mariners-future.html|title=Owners Focus on Mariners' Future|last=Smith|first=Claire|date=1991-09-12|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> the team's losing ways (prior to 1995, they only had two seasons with a [[winning percentage]] over .500),<ref name=\"SEAAtt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/SEA/attend.shtml|title=Seattle Mariners Attendance, Stadiums and Park Factors|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> and the [[Kingdome]]'s [[Kingdome#Baseball|drab baseball environment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ballparksofbaseball.com/past/Kingdome.htm|title=Kingdome - Seattle Mariners|publisher=Ballparks of Baseball|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1992 Seattle Mariners season|1992]], Smulyan's ownership group sold the Mariners to the Baseball Club of Seattle, a [[consortium]] led by [[Hiroshi Yamauchi]]<ref name=\"MsSale\">{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19920609&slug=1496316|title=M's Sale Gets Go-Ahead - Full Acceptance of Offer Predicted for Tomorrow|last=Farrey|first=Tom|author2=Joni Balter |date=1992-06-09|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> and later [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20041130&slug=mari30|title=M's will not be sold|last=Finnigan|first=Bob|date=2004-11-30|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> Almost immediately, the new ownership group began campaigning with local and state governments to gain public funding for a new stadium.  (In 2016, [[Nintendo of America]] sold most shares of Seattle Mariners ownership held by it to a new ownership group, though Nintendo retained a 10% ownership of the team after the sale was completed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/nintendo-to-sell-90-percent-interest-in-mariners-to-group-led-by-john-stanton/|title=Mariners to be sold by Nintendo to ownership group led by John Stanton|last=Divish|first=Ryan|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|date=27 April 2016|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref>)\n\nIn an election held on September 19, 1995, the residents of [[King County, Washington|King County]] voted against a 1-[[percentage-point]] sales tax increase to fund the building of a replacement stadium.<ref name=\"SafecoHist\" /><ref name=\"Licata\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seattle.gov/council/licata/up/up66.htm|title=Urban Politics #66|last=Licata|first=Nick|date=1999-06-27|publisher=Office of Seattle City Councilmember Nick Licata|accessdate=2009-03-30|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603210818/http://www.seattle.gov/council/licata/up/up66.htm|archivedate=May 26, 2018}}</ref> As a result, the ownership group set an October 30 deadline for local leadership to come up with a plan to finance a new stadium, or they would put the team up for sale.<ref name=\"Oct30\">{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950928&slug=2143939|title=M's Set Oct. 30 Deadline|last=Schaefer|first=David|author2=David Postman |date=1995-09-28|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Mariners make the postseason===\nAfter being as many as 13 [[games behind|games out of first place]] at the beginning of August,<ref name=\"95SEAB-R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/SEA/1995_sched.shtml|title=1995 Seattle Mariners Schedule, Box Scores and Splits|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> the Mariners mounted a late-season comeback that, coupled with a late-season collapse by the [[1995 California Angels season|California Angels]],<ref name=\"CALB-R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/CAL/1995_sched.shtml |title=1995 California Angels Schedule, Box Score and Splits|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> forced a [[1995 American League West tie-breaker game|tiebreaker]] between the two teams. The Mariners won the tiebreaker, 9&ndash;1,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA199510020.shtml|title=October 2, 1995 California Angels at Seattle Mariners Box Score and Play by Play|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> winning their first division title and postseason trip in franchise history.\n\nIn the [[1995 American League Division Series|ALDS]], the Mariners quickly fell into a 2\u20130 deficit to the [[1995 New York Yankees season|Yankees]] in the best-of-five series.<ref name=\"ALDSB-R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1995_ALDS2.shtml|title=1995 AL Division Series - SEA vs. NYY|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> However, the Mariners won the next two games and forced a \"winner-takes-all\" Game 5 at the [[Kingdome]].<ref name=\"ALDSB-R\" />\n\n==The play==\nAfter the Yankees took a 4\u20132 lead on a [[Don Mattingly]] 2-[[Run batted in|RBI]] double in the 6th inning, the Mariners came back to tie the score at 4 in the 8th inning and eventually forced [[extra innings]].<ref name=\"B-R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA199510080.shtml|title=October 8, 1995 American League Division Series (ALDS) Game 5 Box Score and Play by Play|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> In the top of the 11th inning, the Yankees scored a run on an [[run batted in|RBI]] single by [[Randy Velarde]] off of Mariners ace [[Randy Johnson]]<ref name=\"B-R\" /> and were three [[out (baseball)|outs]] from reaching the [[1995 American League Championship Series|American League Championship Series]].\n\nIn the bottom half of the inning, Yankees [[Ace (baseball)|ace]] [[Jack McDowell]], who had entered the game in the 9th inning for a rare [[relief pitcher|relief]] appearance, faced [[Joey Cora]], [[Ken Griffey, Jr.]], and [[Edgar Mart\u00ednez]]\u2014the second, third, and fourth batters in the Mariners' [[batting order (baseball)|order]], respectively.<ref name=\"B-R\" /> [[Second baseman]] Cora dragged a [[bunt (baseball)|bunt]] down the [[first base]] line and reached first base [[safe (baseball)|safely]] on an [[infield hit]].<ref name=\"B-R\" /> Yankees manager [[Buck Showalter]] argued the call, believing Cora should have been called out for running off the [[Baseball field#Baseline|baselines]]; however, the [[umpire (baseball)|umpires']] ruling stood. [[Center fielder]] Griffey [[single (baseball)|singled]] to short right-center field, allowing Cora to reach [[third base]].<ref name=\"B-R\" /> [[Designated hitter]] Martinez then doubled down the left field line, scoring Cora with the tying run and Griffey with the winning run.<ref name=\"B-R\" /> The Mariners' [[dugout (baseball)|dugout]] emptied and mobbed Griffey, Martinez, and Cora on the field in celebration of the franchise's first ever playoff series victory.\n\n===Dave Niehaus' call===\n\n{{Listen\n|filename=Dave Niehaus Winning Call 1995 AL Division Series.ogg\n|title=\"1995 AL Division Series Winning Call\"\n|description=The winning call of the 1995 American League Division Series as called by Dave Niehaus, one of his most famous calls.\n|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n[[Dave Niehaus]]'s radio call of the Double is as memorable to Seattle fans as the play itself and became one of the hallmarks of Niehaus's [[Ford C. Frick Award]]-winning career:<ref>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2008075653_niehausx27.html |title=My, oh my, forever |last=Stone |first=Larry |date=2008-07-27 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=2009-03-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090820042439/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2008075653_niehausx27.html |archivedate=August 20, 2009 }}</ref>\n{{cquote|Right now, the Mariners looking for the tie. They would take a [[sacrifice fly|fly ball]]; they would love a [[hit (baseball)|base hit]] into the gap and they could win it with Junior's speed. The stretch and the 0&ndash;1 pitch on the way to [[Edgar Mart\u00ednez]]; swung on and lined down the left field line for a base hit! Here comes Joey! Here is Junior to third base, they're going to wave him in! The throw to the plate will be...LATE! The Mariners are going to play for the [[1995 American League Championship Series|American League Championship]]! I don't believe it! It just continues! My oh My! Edgar Mart\u00ednez with a double ripped down the left field line and they are going crazy at the Kingdome!<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20080220/NEWS01/224243533|title=Hall of Fame for Mariners announcer Dave Niehaus|last=Arnold|first=Kirby|date=2008-02-20|work=[[The Herald (Everett)|The Herald]]|location=[[Everett, Washington]] |accessdate=2009-05-15}}</ref>}}\n\n===Brent Musburger's call===\n[[Major League Baseball on ABC|ABC Sports]] through [[The Baseball Network]] broadcast the Double on television. [[Brent Musburger]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/au/mlb/news/brent-musburger-baseball-announcer-retiring-video-mariners-yankees-1995-alds/14arlwzwhwtlg1mhrb8osn2bos|title=Remember when Brent Musburger called baseball games?\n|last=Foster|first=Jason|date=January 25, 2017|website=Sporting News|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/brent-musburgers-greatest-baseball-call-was-one-for-the-ages-021440813.html|title=Brent Musburger's greatest baseball call was one for the ages|last=Townsend|first=Mark|date=January 25, 2017|website=Big League Stew|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> along with color commentator [[Jim Kaat]] and field reporter [[Jack Arute]] called Game 5:\n{{cquote|No balls and a strike to [[Edgar Mart\u00ednez|Mart\u00ednez]]. Line drive, we are tied! [[Ken Griffey Jr.|Griffey]] is coming around! In the corner is [[Bernie Williams|Bernie]]. He's going to try to score! Here's the division championship! Mariners win it! Mariners win it!}}\n\nMusberger's call, dramatic as it was, incorrectly implied that Bernie Williams fielded the double in left. Bernie was playing center field at the time. [[Gerald Williams (baseball)|Gerald Williams]] was in left field playing the ball and making the late throw back to the infield.\n\n===John Sterling's call===\nIn New York, the Double was described<ref>{{YouTube|title=1995 ALDS, Game 5 Postgame (WABC, MSG)|id=xtlqHRaeXNQ&t}}</ref> on radio by [[John Sterling (sportscaster)|John Sterling]] on [[WABC (AM)|WABC]]:\n{{cquote|The 0-1; the pitch...LINED...base hit down the left field line! The tying run scores! [[Ken Griffey Jr.|Griffey]] heads towards third...he's being sent in! The throw home is...not in time! Seattle wins! Seattle wins the [[1995 American League Division Series|Division Series]] on a double by [[Edgar Mart\u00ednez]]!}}\n\n==Off-field significance and legacy==\n[[Image:Safeco Field night.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[T-Mobile Park]], home of the Mariners since 1999. The Double is credited with helping to spur public funding for T-Mobile Park.]]\n\n===Keeping the Mariners in Seattle===\nThe Mariners' late season comeback, their first division title in franchise history, and ultimately the Double, brought the Seattle fan base back to life and sparked a desire to keep the team in town. [[Lou Piniella]], the Mariners' [[manager (baseball)|manager]] from 1993\u20132002, called Martinez's hit and the 1995 postseason \"the hit, the run, the game, the series and the season that saved baseball in Seattle.\"<ref name=\"ESPNHoF\" /> Soon after the events of October 8, the [[Washington State Legislature]] held a special session and approved an alternative funding package to enable the building of a new ballpark, which culminated in the construction of [[T-Mobile Park]].<ref name=\"SafecoHist\">{{cite web\n |title=Safeco Field History\n | publisher= Seattle Mariners official website\n | url = http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/sea/ballpark/history.jsp\n | accessdate = 2008-06-15\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Licata\" />\n\n===Legacy===\nThe Double is regarded by Seattle fans and Martinez himself as the defining moment of Martinez's 18-year [[Major League Baseball]] career &ndash; which was played exclusively with the Mariners<ref name=\"ESPNHoF\" /><ref name=\"KingofSwing\">{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/baseball/114316_tabedgar28.shtml|title=Edgar Martinez: The king of swing|last=Andriesen|first=David|date=2003-03-28|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> &ndash; and was one of several highlights of Mariners franchise history in which Martinez played a major role.<ref name=\"Finnigan\" /> In 2004, the city of Seattle renamed a street near T-Mobile Park \"Edgar Mart\u00ednez Drive\" to honor Martinez's contributions to the Mariners, including his double that \"saved baseball in Seattle.\"<ref name=\"SeaMayor\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seattle.gov/mayor/newsdetail.asp?ID=4658&dept=40|title=Nickels honors baseball legend with new Edgar Martinez Drive|date=2004-10-04|publisher=City of Seattle Office of the Mayor|accessdate=2009-03-25}} </ref> Martinez was inducted into the Mariners Hall of Fame in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2003732760_marinotes03.html|title=Mariners, fans salute Edgar|last=Romero|first=Jos\u00e9 Miguel|date=2007-06-03|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-05-13}}</ref>\n\nThe image of Griffey at the bottom of the dog-pile after scoring the winning run is one of the most memorable images of Griffey's storied career with the Mariners.<ref name=\"KingofSwing\" /> In [[2007 Seattle Mariners season|2007]], when Griffey returned to Seattle for the first time since his 1999 trade to the [[Cincinnati Reds]], that image was included in a photo collage of highlights of Griffey's Mariners career that was presented to him by former teammates Martinez and [[Jay Buhner]] (both retired by then).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2003759459_griffey23.html|title=Plenty of cheers to greet Griffey|last=Ko|first=Michael|date=2007-06-23|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref>\n\nThe image of Griffey sliding into [[home plate]] has been immortalized in a mural at T-Mobile Park called ''The Defining Moment''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/sea/ballpark/art.jsp|title=Art in the Park|publisher=Seattle Mariners official website|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref>\n\nGriffey's slide into home plate was also the inspiration behind the title of the 1996 video game ''[[Ken Griffey, Jr.'s Winning Run]]''.\n\nThe game would be Buck Showalter's last as Yankees manager and Don Mattingly's final game as a player before his retirement.  During the offseason the Yankees would acquire Mariners first baseman [[Tino Martinez]], who would go on to be part of the [[1996 New York Yankees season|Yankees']] [[1996 World Series]] winning team, their first under new manager [[Joe Torre]].\n\nThe play is featured prominently in [[SB Nation]]'s 3rd episode of ''Dorktown: The History of the Seattle Mariners''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dorktown Episode 3 |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2020/4/9/21214901/the-history-of-the-seattle-mariners-part-3 |website=SB Nation |publisher=SB Nation}}</ref>\n\n==Scoring==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n|+ Summary \u2013 bottom of the 11th inning\n! scope=\"col\"| Pitcher<br><small>New York Yankees</small>\n! scope=\"col\"| Batter<br><small>Seattle Mariners</small>\n! scope=\"col\"| Result<br><small>(outs in bold)</small>\n! scope=\"col\"| Score<br><small>Mariners \u2013 Yankees</small>\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Jack McDowell]] (R) || [[Joey Cora]] (S) || Bunt single || rowspan=2|<center>4\u20135</center>\n|-\n|[[Ken Griffey Jr.]] (L) || Single to center; Cora to third\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddf;|[[Edgar Martinez]] (R) || style=\"background:#ddf;|Double to left; Cora and Griffey scored || style=\"background:#ddf;|<center>6\u20135</center>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[1995 Seattle Mariners season]]\n*[[1995 New York Yankees season]]\n*[[1995 American League Division Series]]\n*[[1995 American League West tie-breaker game]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.baseball-almanac.com/box-scores/boxscore.php?boxid=199510080SEA Box score of The Double game] at [[Baseball Almanac]]\n*[https://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1995/B10080SEA1995.htm Box score of The Double game] at [[Retrosheet]]\n*[http://mlbnetwork.mlb.com/media/video.jsp?content_id=3850040 Griffey's dash home in '95 ALDS]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100119140344/www.mlb.com/mlb/baseballs_best/mlb_bb_gamepage.jsp?story_page=bb_95alds_gm5_nyysea 1995 ALDS Game 5] at MLB.com's \"Baseball's Best\" library via [[Wayback Machine]]\n\n{{Seattle Mariners}}\n{{Major League Baseball on ABC}}\n{{Major League Baseball on CBS Radio}}\n{{The Baseball Network}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Double, The}}\n[[Category:American League Division Series]]\n[[Category:1995 Major League Baseball season]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball games]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners postseason]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees postseason]]\n[[Category:October 1995 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:1995 in sports in Washington (state)]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:The Double.jpg|300px|right|thumb|[[Ken Griffey, Jr.]] (center) and the [[1995 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]] celebrate after he scored the winning run in Game 5 of the [[1995 American League Division Series|1995 ALDS]].]]\n'''The Double''' was a [[double (baseball)|double]] hit by the [[1995 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]]' [[Edgar Mart\u00ednez]] in Game 5 of [[Major League Baseball]]'s [[1995 American League Division Series]] on October 8, 1995. Trailing by one run in the bottom half of the 11th inning, with [[Joey Cora]] on third base and [[Ken Griffey, Jr.]] on first, Martinez's [[hit (baseball)|hit]] [[run batted in|drove in]] Cora and Griffey, giving the Mariners a 6\u20135 victory over the [[1995 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] to clinch the series, 3\u20132. The play is held to be the \"biggest hit in franchise history.\"<ref name=\"ESPNHoF\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=1888518&type=story|title=Martinez is beloved by Seattle fans; what about Hall voters?|last=Associated Press|date=2004-09-25|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref>\n\nAmid rumors that the team would be sold and/or relocated, the Mariners\u2014who had had only two winning seasons ([[1991 Seattle Mariners season|1991]] and [[1993 Seattle Mariners season|1993]]) since beginning play in [[1977 Seattle Mariners season|1977]]\u2014mounted a late-season comeback in [[1995 Seattle Mariners season|1995]] to clinch their first postseason appearance in franchise history. They then mounted a series of comebacks in the ALDS, first overcoming a 2-game series deficit to force a deciding Game 5, then tying Game 5 in the 8th inning to force [[extra innings]], and finally a one-run 11th inning deficit that was overcome by the Double.\n\nThe hit is regarded as the defining moment of Martinez's 18-year [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Fame]] career.<ref name=\"ESPNHoF\" /> Mariners broadcaster [[Dave Niehaus]]' call of the play\u2014which is equally memorable to Seattle fans as the play itself\u2014is also regarded as the highlight of his career. The play is also credited with keeping a Major League Baseball team in the city of [[Seattle]], as it helped garner support for a new taxpayer-funded stadium for the Mariners.<ref name=\"Finnigan\">{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2002001226_edgardecision10.html|title=How Martinez arrived at his decision to retire|last=Finnigan|first=Bob|date=2004-08-10|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"PIAndreisen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/baseball/356292_edgar25.html|title=Will Edgar Martinez head to Hall of Fame?|last=Andriesen|first=David|date=2008-03-25|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> That stadium, known today as [[T-Mobile Park]] (it was originally known as Safeco Field through the end of the [[2018 Seattle Mariners season|2018 season]]), opened in [[1999 Seattle Mariners season|1999]], with the Double depicted in a mural as part of the stadium's art collection.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:USS Leahy (CG-16) in front of the Seattle Kingdome Stadium on 6 October 1982 (6371846).jpg|thumb|right|250px|The [[Kingdome]], the Mariners' home stadium from [[1977 Seattle Mariners season|1977]]&ndash;[[1999 Seattle Mariners season|1999]], and site of The Double.]]\n\n===Relocation rumors===\nFor several years the Mariners had been dogged by rumors that the team's ownership group led by [[Jeff Smulyan]] had been considering selling and/or relocating the team to a different city.<ref name=\"NYT\" /><ref name=\"Ms92\">{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19911211&slug=1322349|title=M's Likely Here in '92|last=Judd|first=Ron|author2=Joni Balter |date=1991-12-11|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> This was primarily due to low attendance and revenue,<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/12/sports/baseball-owners-focus-on-mariners-future.html|title=Owners Focus on Mariners' Future|last=Smith|first=Claire|date=1991-09-12|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> the team's losing ways (prior to 1995, they only had two seasons with a [[winning percentage]] over .500),<ref name=\"SEAAtt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/SEA/attend.shtml|title=Seattle Mariners Attendance, Stadiums and Park Factors|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> and the [[Kingdome]]'s [[Kingdome#Baseball|drab baseball environment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ballparksofbaseball.com/past/Kingdome.htm|title=Kingdome - Seattle Mariners|publisher=Ballparks of Baseball|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1992 Seattle Mariners season|1992]], Smulyan's ownership group sold the Mariners to the Baseball Club of Seattle, a [[consortium]] led by [[Hiroshi Yamauchi]]<ref name=\"MsSale\">{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19920609&slug=1496316|title=M's Sale Gets Go-Ahead - Full Acceptance of Offer Predicted for Tomorrow|last=Farrey|first=Tom|author2=Joni Balter |date=1992-06-09|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> and later [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20041130&slug=mari30|title=M's will not be sold|last=Finnigan|first=Bob|date=2004-11-30|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> Almost immediately, the new ownership group began campaigning with local and state governments to gain public funding for a new stadium.  (In 2016, [[Nintendo of America]] sold most shares of Seattle Mariners ownership held by it to a new ownership group, though Nintendo retained a 10% ownership of the team after the sale was completed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/nintendo-to-sell-90-percent-interest-in-mariners-to-group-led-by-john-stanton/|title=Mariners to be sold by Nintendo to ownership group led by John Stanton|last=Divish|first=Ryan|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|date=27 April 2016|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref>)\n\nIn an election held on September 19, 1995, the residents of [[King County, Washington|King County]] voted against a 1-[[percentage-point]] sales tax increase to fund the building of a replacement stadium.<ref name=\"SafecoHist\" /><ref name=\"Licata\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seattle.gov/council/licata/up/up66.htm|title=Urban Politics #66|last=Licata|first=Nick|date=1999-06-27|publisher=Office of Seattle City Councilmember Nick Licata|accessdate=2009-03-30|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603210818/http://www.seattle.gov/council/licata/up/up66.htm|archivedate=May 26, 2018}}</ref> As a result, the ownership group set an October 30 deadline for local leadership to come up with a plan to finance a new stadium, or they would put the team up for sale.<ref name=\"Oct30\">{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950928&slug=2143939|title=M's Set Oct. 30 Deadline|last=Schaefer|first=David|author2=David Postman |date=1995-09-28|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Mariners make the postseason===\nAfter being as many as 13 [[games behind|games out of first place]] at the beginning of August,<ref name=\"95SEAB-R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/SEA/1995_sched.shtml|title=1995 Seattle Mariners Schedule, Box Scores and Splits|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> the Mariners mounted a late-season comeback that, coupled with a late-season collapse by the [[1995 California Angels season|California Angels]],<ref name=\"CALB-R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/CAL/1995_sched.shtml |title=1995 California Angels Schedule, Box Score and Splits|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> forced a [[1995 American League West tie-breaker game|tiebreaker]] between the two teams. The Mariners won the tiebreaker, 9&ndash;1,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA199510020.shtml|title=October 2, 1995 California Angels at Seattle Mariners Box Score and Play by Play|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> winning their first division title and postseason trip in franchise history.\n\nIn the [[1995 American League Division Series|ALDS]], the Mariners quickly fell into a 2\u20130 deficit to the [[1995 New York Yankees season|Yankees]] in the best-of-five series.<ref name=\"ALDSB-R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1995_ALDS2.shtml|title=1995 AL Division Series - SEA vs. NYY|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> However, the Mariners won the next two games and forced a \"winner-takes-all\" Game 5 at the [[Kingdome]].<ref name=\"ALDSB-R\" />\n\n==The play==\nAfter the Yankees took a 4\u20132 lead on a [[Don Mattingly]] 2-[[Run batted in|RBI]] double in the 6th inning, the Mariners came back to tie the score at 4 in the 8th inning and eventually forced [[extra innings]].<ref name=\"B-R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA199510080.shtml|title=October 8, 1995 American League Division Series (ALDS) Game 5 Box Score and Play by Play|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> In the top of the 11th inning, the Yankees scored a run on an [[run batted in|RBI]] single by [[Randy Velarde]] off of Mariners ace [[Randy Johnson]]<ref name=\"B-R\" /> and were three [[out (baseball)|outs]] from reaching the [[1995 American League Championship Series|American League Championship Series]].\n\nIn the bottom half of the inning, Yankees [[Ace (baseball)|ace]] [[Jack McDowell]], who had entered the game in the 9th inning for a rare [[relief pitcher|relief]] appearance, faced [[Joey Cora]], [[Ken Griffey, Jr.]], and [[Edgar Mart\u00ednez]]\u2014the second, third, and fourth batters in the Mariners' [[batting order (baseball)|order]], respectively.<ref name=\"B-R\" /> [[Second baseman]] Cora dragged a [[bunt (baseball)|bunt]] down the [[first base]] line and reached first base [[safe (baseball)|safely]] on an [[infield hit]].<ref name=\"B-R\" /> Yankees manager [[Buck Showalter]] argued the call, believing Cora should have been called out for running off the [[Baseball field#Baseline|baselines]]; however, the [[umpire (baseball)|umpires']] ruling stood. [[Center fielder]] Griffey [[single (baseball)|singled]] to short right-center field, allowing Cora to reach [[third base]].<ref name=\"B-R\" /> [[Designated hitter]] Martinez then doubled down the left field line, scoring Cora with the tying run and Griffey with the winning run.<ref name=\"B-R\" /> The Mariners' [[dugout (baseball)|dugout]] emptied and mobbed Griffey, Martinez, and Cora on the field in celebration of the franchise's first ever playoff series victory.\n\n===Dave Niehaus' call===\n\n{{Listen\n|filename=Dave Niehaus Winning Call 1995 AL Division Series.ogg\n|title=\"1995 AL Division Series Winning Call\"\n|description=The winning call of the 1995 American League Division Series as called by Dave Niehaus, one of his most famous calls.\n|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n[[Dave Niehaus]]'s radio call of the Double is as memorable to Seattle fans as the play itself and became one of the hallmarks of Niehaus's [[Ford C. Frick Award]]-winning career:<ref>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2008075653_niehausx27.html |title=My, oh my, forever |last=Stone |first=Larry |date=2008-07-27 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=2009-03-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090820042439/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2008075653_niehausx27.html |archivedate=August 20, 2009 }}</ref>\n{{cquote|Right now, the Mariners looking for the tie. They would take a [[sacrifice fly|fly ball]]; they would love a [[hit (baseball)|base hit]] into the gap and they could win it with Junior's speed. The stretch and the 0&ndash;1 pitch on the way to [[Edgar Mart\u00ednez]]; swung on and lined down the left field line for a base hit! Here comes Joey! Here is Junior to third base, they're going to wave him in! The throw to the plate will be...LATE! The Mariners are going to play for the [[1995 American League Championship Series|American League Championship]]! I don't believe it! It just continues! My oh My! Edgar Mart\u00ednez with a double ripped down the left field line and they are going crazy at the Kingdome!<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20080220/NEWS01/224243533|title=Hall of Fame for Mariners announcer Dave Niehaus|last=Arnold|first=Kirby|date=2008-02-20|work=[[The Herald (Everett)|The Herald]]|location=[[Everett, Washington]] |accessdate=2009-05-15}}</ref>}}\n\n===Brent Musburger's call===\n[[Major League Baseball on ABC|ABC Sports]] through [[The Baseball Network]] broadcast the Double on television. [[Brent Musburger]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/au/mlb/news/brent-musburger-baseball-announcer-retiring-video-mariners-yankees-1995-alds/14arlwzwhwtlg1mhrb8osn2bos|title=Remember when Brent Musburger called baseball games?\n|last=Foster|first=Jason|date=January 25, 2017|website=Sporting News|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/brent-musburgers-greatest-baseball-call-was-one-for-the-ages-021440813.html|title=Brent Musburger's greatest baseball call was one for the ages|last=Townsend|first=Mark|date=January 25, 2017|website=Big League Stew|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> along with color commentator [[Jim Kaat]] and field reporter [[Jack Arute]] called Game 5:\n{{cquote|No balls and a strike to [[Edgar Mart\u00ednez|Mart\u00ednez]]. Line drive, we are tied! [[Ken Griffey Jr.|Griffey]] is coming around! In the corner is [[Bernie Williams|Bernie]]. He's going to try to score! Here's the division championship! Mariners win it! Mariners win it!}}\n\nMusberger's call, dramatic as it was, incorrectly implied that Bernie Williams fielded the double in left. Bernie was playing center field at the time. [[Gerald Williams (baseball)|Gerald Williams]] was in left field playing the ball and making the late throw back to the infield.\n\n===John Sterling's call===\nIn New York, the Double was described<ref>{{YouTube|title=1995 ALDS, Game 5 Postgame (WABC, MSG)|id=xtlqHRaeXNQ&t}}</ref> on radio by [[John Sterling (sportscaster)|John Sterling]] on [[WABC (AM)|WABC]]:\n{{cquote|The 0-1; the pitch...LINED...base hit down the left field line! The tying run scores! [[Ken Griffey Jr.|Griffey]] heads towards third...he's being sent in! The throw home is...not in time! Seattle wins! Seattle wins the [[1995 American League Division Series|Division Series]] on a double by [[Edgar Mart\u00ednez]]!}}\n\n==Off-field significance and legacy==\n[[Image:Safeco Field night.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[T-Mobile Park]], home of the Mariners since 1999. The Double is credited with helping to spur public funding for T-Mobile Park.]]\n\n===Keeping the Mariners in Seattle===\nThe Mariners' late season comeback, their first division title in franchise history, and ultimately the Double, brought the Seattle fan base back to life and sparked a desire to keep the team in town. [[Lou Piniella]], the Mariners' [[manager (baseball)|manager]] from 1993\u20132002, called Martinez's hit and the 1995 postseason \"the hit, the run, the game, the series and the season that saved baseball in Seattle.\"<ref name=\"ESPNHoF\" /> Soon after the events of October 8, the [[Washington State Legislature]] held a special session and approved an alternative funding package to enable the building of a new ballpark, which culminated in the construction of [[T-Mobile Park]].<ref name=\"SafecoHist\">{{cite web\n |title=Safeco Field History\n | publisher= Seattle Mariners official website\n | url = http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/sea/ballpark/history.jsp\n | accessdate = 2008-06-15\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Licata\" />\n\n===Legacy===\nThe Double is regarded by Seattle fans and Martinez himself as the defining moment of Martinez's 18-year [[Major League Baseball]] career &ndash; which was played exclusively with the Mariners<ref name=\"ESPNHoF\" /><ref name=\"KingofSwing\">{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/baseball/114316_tabedgar28.shtml|title=Edgar Martinez: The king of swing|last=Andriesen|first=David|date=2003-03-28|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> &ndash; and was one of several highlights of Mariners franchise history in which Martinez played a major role.<ref name=\"Finnigan\" /> In 2004, the city of Seattle renamed a street near T-Mobile Park \"Edgar Mart\u00ednez Drive\" to honor Martinez's contributions to the Mariners, including his double that \"saved baseball in Seattle.\"<ref name=\"SeaMayor\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seattle.gov/mayor/newsdetail.asp?ID=4658&dept=40|title=Nickels honors baseball legend with new Edgar Martinez Drive|date=2004-10-04|publisher=City of Seattle Office of the Mayor|accessdate=2009-03-25}} </ref> Martinez was inducted into the Mariners Hall of Fame in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2003732760_marinotes03.html|title=Mariners, fans salute Edgar|last=Romero|first=Jos\u00e9 Miguel|date=2007-06-03|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-05-13}}</ref>\n\nThe image of Griffey at the bottom of the dog-pile after scoring the winning run is one of the most memorable images of Griffey's storied career with the Mariners.<ref name=\"KingofSwing\" /> In [[2007 Seattle Mariners season|2007]], when Griffey returned to Seattle for the first time since his 1999 trade to the [[Cincinnati Reds]], that image was included in a photo collage of highlights of Griffey's Mariners career that was presented to him by former teammates Martinez and [[Jay Buhner]] (both retired by then).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2003759459_griffey23.html|title=Plenty of cheers to greet Griffey|last=Ko|first=Michael|date=2007-06-23|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref>\n\nThe image of Griffey sliding into [[home plate]] has been immortalized in a mural at T-Mobile Park called ''The Defining Moment''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/sea/ballpark/art.jsp|title=Art in the Park|publisher=Seattle Mariners official website|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref>\n\nGriffey's slide into home plate was also the inspiration behind the title of the 1996 video game ''[[Ken Griffey, Jr.'s Winning Run]]''.\n\nThe game would be Buck Showalter's last as Yankees manager and Don Mattingly's final game as a player before his retirement.  During the offseason the Yankees would acquire Mariners first baseman [[Tino Martinez]], who would go on to be part of the [[1996 New York Yankees season|Yankees']] [[1996 World Series]] winning team, their first under new manager [[Joe Torre]].\n\nThe play is featured prominently in [[SB Nation]]'s 3rd episode of \"Dorktown: The History of the Seattle Mariners\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Dorktown Episode 3 |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2020/4/9/21214901/the-history-of-the-seattle-mariners-part-3 |website=SB Nation |publisher=SB Nation}}</ref>\n\n==Scoring==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n|+ Summary \u2013 bottom of the 11th inning\n! scope=\"col\"| Pitcher<br><small>New York Yankees</small>\n! scope=\"col\"| Batter<br><small>Seattle Mariners</small>\n! scope=\"col\"| Result<br><small>(outs in bold)</small>\n! scope=\"col\"| Score<br><small>Mariners \u2013 Yankees</small>\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Jack McDowell]] (R) || [[Joey Cora]] (S) || Bunt single || rowspan=2|<center>4\u20135</center>\n|-\n|[[Ken Griffey Jr.]] (L) || Single to center; Cora to third\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddf;|[[Edgar Martinez]] (R) || style=\"background:#ddf;|Double to left; Cora and Griffey scored || style=\"background:#ddf;|<center>6\u20135</center>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[1995 Seattle Mariners season]]\n*[[1995 New York Yankees season]]\n*[[1995 American League Division Series]]\n*[[1995 American League West tie-breaker game]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.baseball-almanac.com/box-scores/boxscore.php?boxid=199510080SEA Box score of The Double game] at [[Baseball Almanac]]\n*[https://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1995/B10080SEA1995.htm Box score of The Double game] at [[Retrosheet]]\n*[http://mlbnetwork.mlb.com/media/video.jsp?content_id=3850040 Griffey's dash home in '95 ALDS]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100119140344/www.mlb.com/mlb/baseballs_best/mlb_bb_gamepage.jsp?story_page=bb_95alds_gm5_nyysea 1995 ALDS Game 5] at MLB.com's \"Baseball's Best\" library via [[Wayback Machine]]\n\n{{Seattle Mariners}}\n{{Major League Baseball on ABC}}\n{{Major League Baseball on CBS Radio}}\n{{The Baseball Network}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Double, The}}\n[[Category:American League Division Series]]\n[[Category:1995 Major League Baseball season]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball games]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners postseason]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees postseason]]\n[[Category:October 1995 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:1995 in sports in Washington (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Theonewhoisseveral", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Double_(Seattle_Mariners)"}
